      "Shiloh was the central sanctuary before the temple was built in Jerusalem — a tent-based worship site where the ark of the covenant resided. Pilgrimages were communal affairs; whole families traveled together, offered sacrifices, and shared meals. The sacrificial portions Elkanah distributes aren't just food — they're religious currency, indicators of status and favor. Giving Hannah a double portion is both affection and a public statement that would have sharpened Peninnah's resentment. The scene at the doorpost where Hannah prays silently is notable because most ancient prayer was spoken aloud; silent prayer was so unusual that Eli genuinely didn't recognize it.",
    modernParallel:
      "Think about what it feels like to sit in a room where everyone else seems to have the thing you most want — the career, the relationship, the family, the health — and someone cheerfully tells you that you should be grateful for what you do have. Elkanah's 'Am I not enough?' is every well-meaning friend who has ever said 'just be positive' to someone drowning in grief. It's not malicious. It's just useless.\n\nHannah's prayer is what happens when you stop performing gratitude and actually tell God — or the universe, or your therapist, or your journal — what's really going on. The text says she prayed 'out of her great anxiety and vexation.' Not out of faith. Not out of peace. Out of anguish. And that's the prayer God answers.\n\nThe modern parallel to Eli is every institution that has become so comfortable with its own rituals that it mistakes genuine desperation for disorder. Churches that police how people grieve. Workplaces that penalize honesty. Systems that can only process pain if it arrives in the approved format. Hannah's correction — 'I'm not drunk; I'm devastated' — is a sentence a lot of people are still trying to say out loud.",
