    relationalNote:
      "The Eli-Samuel dynamic is one of the most complex mentor relationships in the Bible. Eli is raising the boy who will replace him. He's training his own succession while watching his biological sons destroy the family name. When the moment comes, Eli doesn't intercept God's word, doesn't spin it, doesn't even ask Samuel to soften the edges. He receives it. The text gives us no indication of bitterness, only acceptance.\n\nSamuel's reluctance to deliver the message is equally important. He 'was afraid to tell the vision to Eli.' This isn't a prophet-in-training eager for his first assignment. It's a boy who loves the old man and is being asked to tell him the worst possible news. Prophetic calling, the text implies, is not about wanting to speak hard truths. It's about speaking them anyway.",
