    modernParallel:
      "Most people have had the experience of hearing something important and running to the wrong source for an explanation. You feel a pull toward a vocation, a relationship, a change — and you explain it away as restlessness, ambition, or indigestion. Samuel's three trips to Eli's bedside are the ancient version of googling your symptoms instead of going to the doctor. Sometimes the voice isn't coming from the direction you expect.\n\nEli's role is equally resonant. He's the person who helps you recognize a calling he himself can't fulfill — the teacher who sees your potential and knows it will eventually render them unnecessary, the parent who realizes their child needs to go somewhere they can't follow. His instruction is simple and devastating: 'Go, lie down, and if he calls you, say, Speak, Lord, for your servant is listening.' He hands Samuel the words for a conversation Eli himself has apparently stopped having.\n\nAnd then there's the morning-after moment: Samuel has the truth, and he doesn't want to say it. Every person who has ever sat on a hard truth — about a friend's marriage, a colleague's performance, an institution's rot — knows this paralysis. The passage doesn't celebrate truth-telling as brave. It presents it as necessary and painful. That's more honest than most motivational posters about 'speaking your truth.'",
